    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <head>
                    <figure>
                        <graphic url="damaskus-moschee-hof-1985.jpg" type="thumbnail" />
                        <head type="imgCaption">Courtesy by Stephan Procházka, 1985</head>
                    </figure>
                </head>
                <div type="typology">
                    <p>Eastern › Syro-Palestinian › Central Syrian</p>
                    <p>Urban, sedentary dialect, high-prestige variety</p>
                </div>
                <div type="general">
                    <p>The dialect of the capital of Syria is regarded as a very “elegant” variety of Arabic
            and has a very high prestige. It is frequently used in the media and increasingly also
            in films. Hence, Damascus Arabic is widely understood in whole Syria, in Lebanon, and
            even in Jordan and Palestine.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="researchHistory">
                    <p>Descriptions of the Arabic dialect of Damascus go back as far as the 18th century when
            the German orientalist and theologian Johann Heinrich Callenberg published his
            description of Damascus Arabic in Latin (<rs type="bibl" ref="zot:callenberg_1720_1740_0000">Callenberg
              (1720-1740)</rs>). Collections of texts and short grammatical notes were published at
            the end of the 19th and the first half of the 20th centuries (<rs type="bibl" ref="zot:huart_0000">Huart (1883)</rs>, <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:oestrup_1897_0000">Oestrup
              (1897)</rs> (although mostly not real Damascene dialect), <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:malinjoud_1924_0000">Malinjoud (1924)</rs>, <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:bergstraser_1924_0000">Bergsträßer (1924)</rs>, <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:saussey_1937_1938_0000">Saussey
            (1937-38)</rs>), <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:cantineau_1956_0001">Cantineau (1956)</rs>, <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:dietrich_1956_0000">Dietrich (1956)</rs>) but the first comprehensive
            description of the dialect appeared only in the 1960s: <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:cowell_1964_0000">Cowell (1964)</rs>, <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:grotzfeld_1964_0000">Grotzfeld (1964)</rs>, <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:grotzfeld_1965_0000">Grotzfeld (1965)</rs>,
              <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:ambros_1977_0000">Ambros (1977)</rs>. Today Damascus Arabic is
            certainly among the Arabic dialects which are best described.</p>
                    <p>A concise grammatical sketch of the dialect is Jérôme Lentin’s “Damascus Arabic”, in
              <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:lentin_2006_0000">EALL I, 546-555</rs>.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="dictionaries">
                    <p>
                        <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:barthelemy_1935_1954_0000">Barthélemy (1935-54)</rs> is still unmatched as the
            dictionary for Syrian Arabic, but it is mainly based on the dialect of Aleppo.
            Nevertheless it is extremely useful for Damascus Arabic too, as is <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:denizeau_1960_0000">Denizeau (1960)</rs>.</p>
                        <p>Very promising is the Dictionnaire d’arabe dialectal syrien (parler de Damas) by Claude
            Salamé &amp; Jérôme Lentin, although until now only the letter B has been published. It
            is available as a <ref target="https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00504180/">free pdf</ref> from the HAL-Server.</p>
                        <p>To obtain a list of dictionaries on Syrian varieties contained in our database <rs type="bibl" ref="bibl:vt:dictionary+bibl:reg:Syria">click here</rs>. </p>
                        <p>VICAV also hosts a small digital dictionary of Damascus Arabic. It was created in
            connection with the Viennese textbooks and primarily serves didactic purposes. You can
            access it <rs ref="text:dictFrontPage_Damascus/DAMASCUS DICTIONARY">here</rs>. </p>
                    </div>
                    <div type="textBooks">
                        <p>The earliest evidence of a textbook in our database is Cantineau/Helbaoui's <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:cantineau_helbaoui_1953_0000">Manuel élémentaire d’arabe oriental (parler de
              Damas)</rs> 1953. Others to be mentioned are Ferguson's <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:ferguson_ani_2nd_edit_1965_0000">Damascus Arabic (1965)</rs>, Rice's <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:rice_sa_id_1966_0000">Eastern Arabic (1979)</rs> and Liddicoat's <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:liddicoat_lennane_1998_0000">Syrian colloquial Arabic: a functional course (1999)</rs>.</p>
                        <p>The Viennese textbook <rs type="bibl" ref="zot:aldoukhi_prochazka_2014_0000 zot:aldoukhi_prochazka_2014_0001">Lehrbuch des
              Syrisch-Arabischen</rs> in two volumes by Aldoukhi, Procházka and Telič is the most
            recent introduction to the dialect of Damascus.</p>
                        <p>To obtain a list of textbooks contained in our database <rs type="bibl" ref="bibl:vt:textbook+bibl:reg:Syria">click here</rs>. </p>
                    </div>
                    <div type="audioData">
                        <p>Songs in Damascus Arabic are abundantly found on YouTube, look for instance for the
            well-known band <ref target="http://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=kulna sawa">Kulna Sawa</ref>.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div type="bibliography">
                        <p>To view publications on this variety click <rs type="bibl" ref="bibl:geo:Damascus">here</rs>.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div type="sampleText">
                        <p>A short sample text is provided <rs ref="sample:damascus_sample_01/Damascus">here</rs>.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div type="lingFeatures">
                        <p>There is a <rs ref="feature:ling_features_damascus/Damascus">list of linguistic
              features</rs> with example sentences.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </body>
        </text>
